title: Historic Blackhawk Hotel
description: The Blackhawk Hotel, listed in theï¿½National Register of Historic Places, is the oldest continuously-operating hotel site in Iowa and is conveniently located in historic downtown Cedar Falls.

title: Hotel Winneshiek
description: The Hotel Winneshiek offers visitors turn-of-the-century charm and grandeur. Located in the scenic river valley country of Northeast Iowa, the Hotel Winneshiek treats visitors to splendidly appointed rooms and suites that encircle an open, three-story atrium. A marble fireplace, a Waterford crystal chandelier, antique furnishings and exquisite millwork create a comfortably inviting atmosphere.

title: Hotel Julien
description: In 1839, travelers' first sight as they crossed the Mississippi River into Dubuque was a hotel building on the corner of 2nd and Main. This old "Julien Hotel" survived a fire, hosted famous guests such as Abraham Lincoln, "Buffalo Bill" Cody and Mark Twain, gained notoriety thanks to Al Capone and was ultimately purchased by the current ownership in 1962. Now 170 years later, after a $30 million interior renovation and exterior restoration, the Hotel Julien Dubuque has redefined elegance through the blending of its rich history with modern luxury and style.

title: Historic Lincoln Hotel
description: The Lincoln Hotel, tucked in the junction of the Old Lincoln and Hoover highways, is located on the southernï¿½ tip of Iowa's Wine Country. Built in 1915, the Lincoln originally hosted workers and travelers on the Pacific and Northwestern Railroads and the Old Lincoln Highway. The Lincoln Hotel was listed on June 28, 1996 in theï¿½National Register of Historic Placesï¿½and is located in Cedar County, Iowa. This restored gem offers spacious suites comfortably furnished in rural America.ï¿½ Enjoy warm midwestern hospitality in a quiet small town setting.

title: Hotel Fort Des Moines
description: Hotel Fort Des Moines has been catering to the needs and wishes of travelers since 1919. Soviet premiere Nikita Khrushchev stayed at the hotel in 1959.  President Nixon also stayed at the hotel, prior to his resignation.

title: Historic Park Inn Hotel
description: The Park Inn Hotel is the last remaining hotel that was designed and built by architect Frank Lloyd Wright.  It is an internationally renowned hotel and architechtural wonder.  The hotel has a unique blend of historical beauty, impressive architecture and modern amenties.

title: Des Moines Renaissance Savery Hotel
description: The Renaissance Savery Hotel stands as an elegant architectural landmark in the heart of downtown Des Moines. The hotel has over 200 guest rooms and 10,000 square feet of event space. It is centrally located in the downtown Des Moines business and entertainment district and is within walking distance of the Iowa Events Center, Wells Fargo Arena and Des Moines Performing Arts.

title: Hotel Pattee
description: The historic Hotel Pattee invites guests to relax in a setting that celebrates the sights and sounds, the people and memories of small town America. The Pattee is one of the few hotels where every room and suite tells its own story. Forty individually decorated and themed guest rooms preserve history, celebrate ethnicity, honor craftsmanship, and pay tribute to the noteworthy sons and daughters of Iowa and the Midwest.

title: Historic Park Motel
description: The Park Motel is a Spanish Colonial Revival building, with simple style distinguished by red tile roofs, stucco walls and heavy wooden doors in round-arch openings. The Park Motel is located along the Lincoln Highway, America's original coast-to-coast route.

title: Hotel Ottumwa
description: Family owned and operated, Hotel Ottumwa is Ottumwa's only full service hotel.  It is conveniently located in historic downtown Ottumwa, within walking distances to attractions and the Amtrak station. Hotel Ottumwa offers a variety of room styles and boasts Southeast Iowa's finest meeting and banquet facilities, including a grand ballroom.

title: Musser Barn
description: The Musser barn was built about 1910 by a wealthy lumber family as a show pavilion for cattle breeding stock sales. The barn has unique open span laminated beam construction and the ground floor has 12-foot high ceilings. The barn's lower level is still in the original configuration of having exhibition pens for sales of their Oakridge Farms breeding stock. The pens had steel gates that allowed easy viewing of the animals. The gates are still in place. In more recent history, the Albert Timm family purchased the Musser farm and used the buildings for their dairy operation for many years. The farm has been sold once again to a group that is working to establish an agricultural learning center, to be operated in conjunction with the Muscatine High School and Muscatine Community College. (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: The Inn at Okoboji
description: The Inn at Okoboji has been a vacation destination since 1896.  It is located on West Lake Okoboji and has 350 feet of shoreline.  The Inn at Okoboji combines traditional charm with over-the-top customer service.

title: Coyner Barn
description: Bricklayers came through Muscatine in the late 1800's and built barns and houses, including the interesting Coyner barn. This attractive brick barn is a very prominent feature on Highway 22, located a few miles West of Muscatine. In years past, dairy cows were milked in the barn. Today, it is still used to house cattle. The unique diamond designs in the brick are actually openings in the barn walls for ventilation. The farm was purchased in 1905 by Kenton Coyner's grandfather. The barn was on the farm at the time, and the Coyner's think it was built about 1890. There used to be a dirt ramp and a wooden bridge leading up to the big white sliding doors that opened up to the upper area to allow wagons with grain to be unloaded into overhead bins. Hay was stored above the grain bins. In the winter, wagons were also housed on this upper level of the barn. There is an unused stairway leading to the cupola which had shutters on all sides at one time. (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Stange Barn
description: This barn, which, dates back to the 1870's, is on the Donald Stange home farm. The Stange's purchased the farm in 1943. The barn had 6 horse stalls which were removed later to make space for present day laying hens. The barn is also now home to a flock of sheep. The barn has unusual, vertical support poles that are hand-hewn oak trees, that were most likely from trees growing nearby. The oak trees were originally so thick in this area that very little grass grew beneath them, and the pastures at the time could support very few cows per acre. The oak pole main supports in this barn remain in very sturdy condition to this day. Note that the sawn cross members are bolted to the oak vertical supports. It was most likely easier to drill bolt holes into the tough oak than it was to drive spikes into the wood. (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Historic Tremont Inn on Main
description: The Tremont Building has been a Marshalltown landmark since 1874.  Originally a three story walk-up hotel, it was destroyed by fire in 1902 and rebuilt in 1904. Renovated in phases, with care and attention to historic detail, this Main Street anchor boasts two great restaurants, four private condiminums and a small, exclusive boutique hotel.

title: Hotel Greenfield
description: Hotel Greenfield was built in 1920. It is the largest commercial building in the central buisiness district. Many early hotel patrons traveled to town by the Chicago, Burlington & Quincy freight-passenger train and were shuttled from the south Greenfield depot.

title: Thompson Seven Springs Farm
description: James and Linda Thompson now own the beautiful Seven Springs farm. The barn has double walls for warmth and still has its original Louden materials handling equipment.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Sywassink Barn
description: The turn-of-the-century Sywassink barn is still in use today. It is a basement barn, and still houses stock cows and calves below the hay mow level. The driveway up to the haymow level is still in place and used. Storage bins for oats and corn were on the hay mow level, and had discharge chutes down into the lower livestock level. In earlier days, cows were milked on the west side in the lean-to addition. Mules were used for field work at one time. (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Stein Barn
description: The grandfather of Paul Stamler, the previous owner, bought this farm in 1903, and had the barn built in 1924 for $3000. The barn was built without proper braces, so the roof eventually started to sag, which required the later installation of additional braces. The lean-to at the rear of the barn was added in mid-1950's. The barn has an usually high peak, making the distance from the hay mow floor to the top very high, so the barn could hold a great amount of loose hay. A barn dance was once held in this cavernous loft. The Stamler's milked 35 cows in the barn with Surge Milkers. The milk was then cooled and then poured into milk cans. A local dairy came by each day at 9AM to pick up the cans of milk. (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Steve Brown Barn
description: The exterior of the Steve Brown barn might be simple, but inside is a very interesting example of 1902-vintage state-of-the-art architecture. Inside the barn is a bucket elevator and a device to unload grain wagons into interior grain bins. The large haymow is impressive and there is a complicated framework holding up the big roof and the overhead haytrack is still in place. Hay wagons with loose hay came into the barn and the hay went up to the mow through an interior opening in the ceiling at that part of the barn. There is a lot of barn graffiti that is on many of the doors, and is a bit of history in itself. The lower floor where the livestock is brick, which is very unusual for a barn. Many of the basement livestock stalls are still intact. The foundation is of large limestone rocks.  The barn presents a very large surface area to winds, which were taking their toll on this old barn, causing it to lean. Steve Brown installed a series of cables on it to straighten the barn, and installed a steel roof and siding to save the barn from rain. Steve says he didn't restore this barn, but he rescued it. Without his recent efforts it surely would have been gone by now.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Kaalberg Barn
description: The turn-of-the-century Kaalberg barn has a large boiler-steel tank water works. This huge tank goes all the way up to the hay loft! The barn, with its distinctive cupola and windows, is on an acreage that is now within western city limits of Muscatine. Cows were milked on the barn's West side. The former milking area is now a shop. An interior wooden corn crib, with upper access doors for scooping corn in, is located on the Southeast corner. The barn has a large hay mow, with hay carrier track still in place. (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: IdleNot/Sywassink Barn
description: The Idlenot barn is on the Sywassink farm purchased in the 1880's by Joyce Schultz's great- grandfather, John Sywassink. Joyce grew up on this farm, and now is a nurse, but in years past she helped milk cows in this barn, as well as to help mow and bale hay. It is thought that this barn replaced an earlier barn that was destroyed by fire. Cows were milked in stanchions that stretched the length of barn on the east side. The hay mow on the North side (the side facing the road) went all the way to the floor for about 1/3rd of the length of the barn. On the south 2/3rd of the barn, the hay mow had a floor above stalls for up to 9 draft horses, and calf pens. A unique gutter system on the west roof is thought to be similar to what might be found on barns is certain parts of Germany. (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Heine Barn
description: The Heine barn sits above the Upper Iowa River and was built in 1903 by immigrants. The barn has a limestone foundation. The Amish recently restored the barn.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Corriell Barn
description: The Corriell farmstead is at the end of a long lane. This farm came into the Corriell family in 1907, and 2007 marks 100 years of ownership by them. Wayne Corriell is very proud of this farm's heritage. Everything on this farm is very well taken care of. There are about 21 buildings on the farm. The earliest is a barn that dates back to the 1870's when it was a house at that time. All the overhead wiring between buildings has recently been put underground. A replacement for the original Aermotor windmill has recently been placed on the old tower. There is a scale house that is still used, that dates back to the early 1900's.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Petersen Barn
description: This century farm has been in the Petersen family since the 1850's, and for the last three generations has passed down from mother to daughter, which is unusual for an Iowa farm. This side of the family has its roots in the Schleswig-Holstein dairy area of Northern Germany. The Petersen's presently milk 100 cows.  In 1915, a spark from a threshing machine started a fire which took all of the buildings, except the house, and destroyed the crops in the surrounding fields on both sides of the roads. The Petersen's rebuilt from that fire, but in 1943 there was another fire during the bitter winter when someone tried to thaw a frozen water pipe with a blow torch. Twenty four hours later a lingering spark was fanned into a blaze by the wind, and again all the buildings except the house were lost.  The Petersen's didn't rebuild immediately because it was during the war and everything was expensive and scarce. Finally in 1945 the decision was made to rebuild, but this time all the walls of the barn, corn crib, and two hog buildings were made from fireproof masonry. The roofs were of fire retardant asbestos shingles. The barn's haymow floor is poured concrete, which has to be very rare. Big steel I-beams support the tremendous weight of the floor. Only the roof rafters and doors were of wood.  The round masonry crib was unique due to its great height and capacity compared to other round cribs built in Iowa, and also for its interior grain bin design. Ear corn was stored on the outside circumference going all the way to the rafters, with grain bins inside providing a large amount of overhead storage. You would think that the Petersen's would be all set by now...but then a tornado came along and tried to twist the upper part of the crib off. Luckily the crib was half full of corn, which saved the building, but much of the top of the structure was nevertheless shifted around 2 to 3 degrees. If the crib had been empty, it probably would have been completely blown away.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Emery Bridge Barn
description: The Norwegian-American bridge barn (laave bru) was built in Norwegian settlements between 1871 and 1906. It combines a characteristic internal bridge found in most Norwegian barns with post and beam building methods of 19th century American barns. The Norwegian bridge barn differs from the European bank barn in that the bridge is an internal structure, one bay wide, extending from the drive-in side access to the opposite side of the building and is above the hay floor level on either side. The external ramp leads to the internal bridge.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Halverson-Huinker Barn
description: An article in the Decorah Journal in 1942 claimed this stone barn was built 75 years earlier. The walls are three feet thick. It is believed Torger Moen may have built the barn.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Ashmore-Jewell Barn
description: This 10,000 square foot barn can trace its history back to 1868 and English settlers, Captain Anderson Ashmore and Thomas Filbert. After a bad wheat harvest in 1874, Ashmore returned to England, and Jacob Jewell, Yankee settler, bought the place and built a second barn. In the 1880's, Jewell's son, Frank, added another section and at the turn-of-the-century, the barns were connected and the long section extended. Frank sold it to Luther College in 1929. The barn housed the livestock that provided milk, meat, and eggs for the college students and staff until the 1960's. The barn was recently restored by Amish.  (Source:  Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Gribble Barn/Czech Dairy Barn
description: Original owners (1855) were Mary and Joseph Puffer. Their son Michael and wife Rose Puffer, built the wooden barn and six surrounding buildings from 1900-1905. The Prague-born Puffers raised Brown Swiss, known for their "rich cream." Community dances were held in the barn. Sherry Puffer Gribble, great granddaughter of the original owners, and her husband, Dale, meticulously restored the barn and farm.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Early Log Barns
description: These two barns may be among the only log barns left in Iowa. It is believed the large barn was built in 1868. Orville Nelson owned these primitive barns for years.  Note:  The barns are about one mile distant from each other.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: 12-Sided Schroeder Barn
description: This unique barn, owned by Charles and Nancy Schroeder, has continually been used in farming since it was built.ï¿½ (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: 12-Sided Thomas Reburn Barn
description: A traveling crew built this 12-sided silo barn in 1914. It was built to feed cattle on the first floor where a manger surrounds the silo base. It is on the National Register of Historic Places. As in the beginning, the name of the owner is Tom Reburn, and he still fills the silo for feeding cattle.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)ï¿½

title: Jacobson Barn
description: This barn was built in two phases - the original stone portion in the late 1850's and the south frame addition in 1888. The original owner was a subsistence farmer while his son expanded farm operations and built the board and batten frame addition onto the stone portion. The Jacobson Farmstead is a National Register Historic Site and owned by the Vesterheim Museum.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Pickar Barn
description: This large barn was painstakingly restored over three years by David Pickar. David had worked diligently on the barn for two years when someone from Dan Marino's chain of restaurants stopped by and asked to buy the barn's wood!  David and Ruth have received an Iowa Barn Foundation Award of Distinctionï¿½for the project. This barn was featured in the Fall 2000 edition of the Iowa Barn Foundation Magazine.ï¿½ (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Handsaker Barn
description: The Handsaker barn, featured on the cover of the Spring 2003 edition of the Iowa Barn Foundation Magazine, is a spartan, unique square barn known widely as the "Fernald barn." William Handsaker bought the rich land, on which the barn stands, from the government in 1853 for $4 per acre. The barn was built in 1880 by J.W. Handsaker, great-great grandfather of Gary Handsaker, who with his mother, Gloria, owns the farm now. Dale Handsaker, Gloria's husband and Gary's father, was a well-known Story County farmer until his death. The beautifully maintained house on the farm was built in 1875. Gary plans to remove the shingle siding on the barn and bring back the original wood and paint it red as it was originally. Interestingly, the Handsaker family sold some of their land so that the village of Fernald could be built.ï¿½ (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Bowman Round Barn
description: Not much is known about the history of the only remaining round barn in Story County. Written on the inside of the barn is "1911 Belcher". The clay tile barn has interesting interior construction and a working track.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Kalsem Barn
description: The Kalsem Barn was built in the late 1800's by Ole J. and Anna (Nelson) Kalsem. The pegged barns were built in the late 1800's. Ole's son, Orville and wife, LaVerne (Ersland) bought the farm in the 1940's. Sons, John and Dave, bought part ownership in the farm in 1965 and are now sole owners. Dave and Mike and their families live in two houses on the farm.ï¿½ (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Freeland Barn
description: Ole Apland was one of six Norwegian men who traveled from Illinois to the "land of milk and honey" and settled near Huxley in the 1860's. Ole Apland built the barn in 1875 five years before his untimely death. Original carving, arguably written by Ole Apland in English and Norwegian, marks date construction was completed: "This building is built by Jens Russell from Cambridge in year 1875."  The barn, 80 feet long, has a basement where corn was dumped for the cattle. ï¿½Structural beams are walnut.  Kermit Freeland, great-grandson of the original owner, and his bride, Flora, moved onto the century farm in 1932.  Kermit passed away in 1984 - but his widow, Flora, owned the farm until well into her 90s.  Until her death in 2007, she was proud of the huge pegged barn and house that was built in 1865. Barn sits in historic Norwegian settlement and remains in the original family.(Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Lowman-Johnson Barn
description: The Lowman-Johnson Barn, built around 1890, is situated on a picturesque, well-cared for farm near Slater, Iowa. It had some restoration in the 1950's. The barn, which houses Dennis and Norma Johnson's horses, was owned by Frank and Edith Lowman for 35 years. The barn illustrates how a small barn can become a piece of art.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: O'Neill Dairy-Hassebrock Barn
description: The O'Neill Dairy, owned by brothers Clem and Henry, was an Ames institution in the 50's and 60's. The large cow herd provided about half of the milk consumed in Ames. Vince Hassebrock, who grew up a mile from the dairy, and his wife bought the farm from the O'Neill estate in 1969. The Hassebrocks actively farm.ï¿½ (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Rosenfeld Barn
description: The Rosenfeld Barn was built around 1918, on land George Rosenfeld purchased in 1873, to house a nationally recognized purebred herd of Aberdeen-Angus cattle. In 1923 the Rosenfeld herd had the International Grand Champion Aberdeen-Angus Cow at Chicago. And, in 1925 the herd produced the Grand Champion Herd of steers over all breeds at Chicago. The huge (96 feet by 66 feet) barn has a poured concrete foundation that goes up inside walls higher than usual. Cattle rubbed against the concrete instead of wood leaving less deterioration. The pegged barn has 27 four-paned windows for light and ventilation. Buyers from throughout the United States used to attend breeding stock sales at the barn. The barn passed from George to Carl to Clyde. It is now owned by Mrs. Beth Rosenfeld Young and Mrs. Ronald Rosenfeld.ï¿½ (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Vos Barn
description: The Vos family barn was built in 1929 by the De Kock family of Pella. It was constructed with commercial milled lumber, round nails, and factory-made windows-modern materials at the time. The barn featured a 10-stanchion milking parlor with cement gutter, stalls for four draft horse teams, and a large hayloft. The barn was purchased in 1992 by Rob and Teri Vos.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Catt Barn
description: This is the barn on the farm where Carrie Chapman Catt grew up.  The 10-acre site is operated by the 19th Amendment Society.

title: Nibbelin Barn
description: John and Doris Nibbelin's barn was built in the 1840's and has been in the family for 95 years. The wooden track is still in the peak of the barn. John's father once had a team of horses on the second floor, which was accessed by the earthen ramp on the north side. One horse lost its footing and fell down while hitched to its teammate.ï¿½ (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Slycord Barn
description: The Slycord barn, which housed Garden City Dairy, is a landmark in Pella. Once two clay block silos separated the barns. These were later removed, and the two barns were joined by a breezeway, now a workshop. The Langstraat family built the south barn in 1909 and the north barn in 1925. The south barn is pegged and has a limestone foundation, The north barn has a clay block foundation. Don and Marcia Slycord own the barn which was purchased by Don's grandparents in 1944. The Slycords use the barn for Simmental cattle. Artist Frank Miller, long-time Des Moines Register cartoonist, once painted a watercolor of the barn.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)ï¿½

title: Young Barn
description: A rare round barn owned by Amy Young and Marlys (Young) and Jack McMeanes. The barn, built in 1911, is 76 feet in diameter and houses a 14-foot cement stave silo. The barn features feed bunks, grain cribs, and a wing shed for horses. The barn was bought by J. Thomas Young in 1958 for use in his feed and grain business, Marion County Produce, Knoxville.ï¿½ (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Taylor County Round Barn
description: This large round barn was built south of Lenox by J.E. Cameron in 1907. It deteriorated, was split into two sections, and moved to its present site. Original materials were used where possible. The barn is 50 feet high, 70 feet in diameter, and 220 feet in circumference. A circular track hangs from the haymow floor supporting a Louden Litter Bucket.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Campbell Barn
description: The Campbell barn was built in the early 1900's. Earl Campbell purchased the site in 1952 and with friends used a dragline and dynamite to dig out adjoining feed lot and a large basement. Each summer Earl and neighbors bought a load of sheep from the West. The western sheep were not familiar with corn and were turned loose in early fall to eat the foxtail and lower corn leaves prior to corn harvest. This helped farmers because there was little "trash" to plug the corn picker. A fourth generation of Campbells is farming the land.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Merlin Hulse Barn
description: The barn is one mile south of ï¿½newï¿½ Highway 30. Clydesdale horses are housed in this barn.

title: Grandview Farm Barn
description: Grandview Farm barn was built in 1861 by Miles Prine who purchased the 95 acres from the James Pomeroy estate in 1861. The farm had been homesteaded in 1849 by the Pomeroys. The name G.S. Prine is painted on one of the grain bin doors. George was a son of Miles who died in 1900. In 1905, Gerrit and Cornie Dykstra purchased the farm and owned it until Pete Vos, father of the present owners, Marion and Dorothy Vos, purchased it in 1945. The beams of the barn are oak and pine. Hand-hewn pegs can be seen in several areas. The ropes that were used for lifting hay to the loft are hanging where Marion placed them in 1953 after the last load of hay was raised.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Donahue Barn
description: This lovely well-kept barn is just off Highway 30 between Dewitt and Grand Mound. Barn has glass bowl fire extinguishers. The farm was named for original maple grove that surrounded log cabin before barn was built.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Scheer Barn
description: The Scheer barn was built by Mrs. Scheer's family in 1881 and was recently meticulously restored. The interior has a wooden silo.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Keith and Lois Whitlatch Barn
description: King Avenue is a north/south gravel road one-half miles west of Stanwood.ï¿½The Whitlatchs raise Belgians in their barn.

title: Forest Johnson Barn
description: This barn is on the west edge of Mechanicsville where the paved street turns to gravel.

title: McGregor Barn
description: The McGregor barn is one of the remaining original barns in the area. It was built in 1883 with a limestone first story and original hand hewn pegged mortise and tenon construction.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Milner Barn
description: The Milner barn was built in 1903 by Don Milner's grandfather. Neighbors turned out to see the new style barn built without the use of wooden pegs.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Formanek Barn
description: Gambrel roof barn is interesting layout with three Dutch doors on the south side.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Jackson Barn
description: This is a horse and cattle barn bought by the Jackson Family in 1964.

title: Marland Acres
description: This weathered barn was built sometime around 1890 and was put together with wooden pegs.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: McDonald Barn
description: There are two historic barns on this beautiful farm. The original barn was built in 1876, but a storm blew the barn across the road in 1898. The family picked up the barn's pieces and rebuilt in 1903. The barn has 12x12-foot mortise and peg boards.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Geirger Barn
description: The barn was built in the 1870s by Blanks Moody Baldwin from native walnut using wooden pegs and limestone boulders for the foundation.ï¿½ At one time horse races were held on a dirt track across the road.ï¿½ People gathered to attend the races and watch the owner's horse, Pluto, run.ï¿½ The barn was originally painted yellow and is now red.ï¿½ The barn has weathered two tornadoes and is without its cupola and weather vane.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Baylor Barn
description: ï¿½The Baylor barn was built in the early 1890s by a crew under the ownership of Ransdell Baylor, who was born in 1850.ï¿½ It is mortised and pegged -- the poles used in raising are lying in the loft.ï¿½ It is 40x 60 feet and built for horses.ï¿½ The barn has been beautifully maintained through the years. (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Birkby Barn
description: the barn was built about 1870 as a basement horse barn with the stalls in the basement and grain bins and small equipment storage on second floor and hay mows overhead.ï¿½ Three fourths of the original brick foundation was replaced in the 1920s and is vulnerable.ï¿½ The barn was also damaged by a tornado in 1948 and rebuilt keeping original bins and stalls in place.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Shirley Barn
description: The Shirley family has been in Fremont County since 1858.ï¿½ They bought their land about 1860.ï¿½ The barn was built by the family about 1940.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Hodde Barn
description: The 100-year-old farm was purchased by Fred Hodde after saving money earned from helping people pick corn by hand.ï¿½ The farm has been home to Hoddes since then.ï¿½ It is believed the barn was built in the early 1900s.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Johnson Barn
description: The barn is on the northeast corner of the intersection of M12 and B 53.ï¿½Barn was built about 1920 for John Adams, a dairy farmer.ï¿½ It has a footprint of over 2000 square feet. Twin cupolas and horse weathervanes are original. Arched rafters had to be hoisted in place with pulleys and horse power. This allowed for access to the loft without support poles.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Belfrage Barn
description: Owner Winston Belfrageï¿½s great-grandfather, John Belfrage, bought the land on which this barn stands in 1875 after serving in the Civil War. A carpenter named Aaron Gunderson built the barn on the land in 1910.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Ascherl Barn
description: This landmark barn was built in 1914 by Mr. Diers from Germantown. ï¿½It is 60 x 54 feet.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Roghair Barn
description: This farm was purchased by Roghair family in 1935 and has a magnificent collection of carefully maintained original buildings including 1911 summer kitchen and 1916 barn.ï¿½ The proud farm is still used for agriculture.ï¿½ (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Kochersperger /Allen Barn
description: Jacob Kochersperger farm has been in the family since 1870.  Barn was built in 1941 and is a treasure on the landscape.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Battaglioli Barn
description: This is one of the few large barns left in the area.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Jensen Barn
description: Barn with attached milk house was built in 1938.  Track and carriage in hayloft are still used to lift hay into the barn.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Mickelson Barn
description: This huge (100x70x45) and distinct barn was built in 1901 to house 22 work horses.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Clancy Barn
description: Barn was built in 1948 by Leo Clancy, charter member of Charlois Association, who raised the cattle on the farm.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Tenold Barn
description: Barn is across from what was the town of Tenold on the Iowa map until 1960.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Ferguson Barn
description: Barn and landmark "conehead" crib were built in 1912. Elevator still works.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Haugen Barn
description: Barn was built in 1915.ï¿½ In 1924 Peter Haugen enlarged it using a handsaw to split the barn in two.ï¿½ He added to the middle.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Rockafellow Barn
description: Beautiful bank barn, with a limestone foundation, was built in 1877 for horses and cattle. The timber was framed with wooden pegs.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Chizek Barn
description: Barn was built by ownerï¿½s grandfather, Albert Chizek, in 1942.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Dreyer Barn
description: The farm has been in the family since 1900; barn was built in 1903 and used as dairy barn until 1944.ï¿½ There is a 1000-gallon wooden water storage tank in hayloft. Manure unloading system is intact.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Yezek Barn
description: This 32- x 52-foot barn with metal cupola was built in 1930 and is one of the only barns standing in the area.ï¿½ The barn was in vulnerable condition when the Yezeks started the restoration project.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Younker Family Heritage Farm Barn
description: This large (112x30) barn has been in the same family since the barn was built in the late 1800's.ï¿½ Inside the barn is a 16'x24' wooden silo that was manufactured by the Indiana Silo company and was built around 1909.ï¿½ This landmark barn was recently lovingly restored by Eleanor Tostlebe Peterson and family.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Dodd Barn
description: Barn was built by Ernest Aldinger, one of three Aldinger brothers who built farms within a mile of each other.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Klousia Barn
description: The barn of peg construction is on a hill on a gorgeous farmstead.ï¿½ The owner copied a Wisconsin dairy barn when he built it in 1888. The barn was proudly placed on the most prominent position on the farm.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: McBurney Barn
description: Stephen Taft, who founded Springvale which became Humboldt, owned the land on which this barn stands.ï¿½ In 1874 he sold the land to Lorbeers who built the house and barn, both still in use.ï¿½ The barn was built in 1890.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Welter Barn
description: Original blueprints developed by Agricultural Engineering Department, Iowa State.ï¿½ It was built in 1947.ï¿½ Working farm was purchased in 1867 by Ole Johnson and has been in the same family since.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Bennett Barn
description: This handsome clay tile barn, with round laminated rafter roof, was built in 1950 by Henning Construction Company, Latimer, for a dairy herd. The cow stanchions had drinking cups; there is a chain lift manure carrier.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: James Michels Barn
description: Redwood tongue and groove 40ï¿½x 80ï¿½ barn was built in 1947.ï¿½ The family has raised Angus cattle since 1947.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Chimney Rock Ranch Barn
description: Large building is corn crib, granary, hog barn, and machine shed and was built in two parts in 1907-08. The corncrib/granary has a basement for hogs. The second part was added to the north end of the original building later that year or the next year.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Lea-Oakley Barn
description: Native limestone Norwegian barn was built by John Johnson in 1862. Original materials are in tact.ï¿½ Barn has a gambrel roof with wooden shingles that was probably added at a later date.ï¿½ Original roof would have been a gable roof.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Marlow-Saak Barn
description: Barn, built in 1890s, is 70x40. Saak family names are on interior. "As an immigrant form England and recent American citizen, I have come to realize Midwestern barns are like the churches and cathedrals of Europe in scale and importance to the landscape,ï¿½ wrote the owner.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Hotvedt Barn
description: John McMullens bought farm from government in 1852 for $1.25 and acre. Nearby Mable, Minnesotaï¿½s steam engine days started on the farm. Farm was in family until 1990.ï¿½ (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Dighton Barn
description: Round barn on National Register was built in 1914 by Rob Kirkpatrick, grandfather of owner. It is intricate.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Geschke Barn
description: Barn, on a hill on US 63, was built in the 1940s.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Finken Barn
description: Roof has laminated rafters which were raised into place with gin pole and horses.ï¿½ Each rafter is five boards thick bolted together and cut in curved shape.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Renze Barn
description: Farm was known as ï¿½Old Mattes Place.ï¿½  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Sparks Barn
description: E.ï¿½G. Herman, 1923, Dubuque, is painted on west inside wall of this very large barn.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Caltrider Barn
description: Farm has been in same family since 1883.ï¿½ Simple barn was built in 1917.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Hinderaker Barn
description: The original barn was built at the turn of the century.ï¿½ It burned down in 1931, and the present barn was built.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Heflin Barn
description: Once there were several of these unique barns in the area, but this is the only one remaining.ï¿½ The barn, built in 1901 and featuring a roofline of four equidistant gabled sides, has been used by four generations of Heflins.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Uetz Barn
description: Barn built by William Smalley, well-known Boone County farmer.ï¿½ Original buildings are on farm including chicken house where family lived in the beginning.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Pfantz Barn
description: Unique horse barn (behind Victorian house) was built in 1902 for Pfantzï¿½s great-grandfather, well-known horse broker. The barn has such unique features as handmade screens and a milk cellar. Note the balloon rafters.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Twedt Barn
description: This barn has 40 two-ply laminate rafters to support its rounded roof so the hayloft is free of posts and beams. Farm was once owned by Hoyt Sherman, brother of the Civil War general. This is a wonderful example of how a small barn can highlight a farm.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Gary Richardson Barn
description: Barn was built in the mid-1940s.ï¿½ Much of the wood used in the interior was from wood used in clearing the land.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Ellis Barn
description: Landmark red barn, used to raise Red Rock Arabians, is called the ï¿½big red barnï¿½ by locals. It was built in 1918 and is 40 feet high to the eaves. It has 3x12-inch timbers.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Oakdale Farm/Grave of Farceur
description: The barn, where Farceur, the world-famous Belgian was buried in 1921, is one of Iowa's hidden treasures.  C.G. Good bought 12-year-old Farceur, the San Francisco World's Fair champion, for $47,000 in 1915.  The horse was a service stud, and, to this day, Farceur's name is on pedigrees of Belgians.  Following a European custom, Good buried the horse in the stall of the stud barn-standing up.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Purviance Barn
description: Local craftsmen built this historic family farm in 1913 for Robert Purviance, prominent Dallas County farmer.ï¿½ The house and two barns are original.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Lang Barn
description: This early twentieth century brick barn is a landmark in Grinnell.ï¿½ It is restored.ï¿½ A smaller barn, across the road, was built in 1896 and is used for agriculture.ï¿½ (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Ihde Barn
description: Barn was designed to emphasize the short, compact body of Angus via two contrasting ceiling levels and higher center alley floor as compared to pen floor.ï¿½ Ceiling above cattle made cattle appear to have larger body size relative to the space they occupied.ï¿½ Beginning farmers are restoring the farm.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Richards Barn
description: The Thornburgh Home Place shows off all of the original buildings, which have been lovinglyï¿½ preserved, including a 1930s milking barn with original stanchions.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Hanson Barn
description: Barn was built in 1907 with wood from older barn demolished by a tornado.ï¿½ Pegged barn was built by Elmer Haley and the Hansons.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Strabala Barn
description: This large barn was built in the 1920's by distinguished United States Senator Smith Brookhart while he was in office.ï¿½ The barn was featured in the article "Washington County resident restores senator's farmstead" inï¿½Iowa Farmer Today.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Clasen Barn
description: Wider-than-usual barn has bark on support timbers.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Delaney Barn
description: This lovely farm is known as the Sprank farm.ï¿½ The large barn was built around 1900, and the smaller one in 1940.ï¿½ The large barn has wooden peg construction.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Steines Barn
description: This simple, primitive barn was built in the early 1900s.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: DeFries Barn
description: The 47 x 84-foot barn was built in 1885 by A.B. DeFries whose family settled in the area in the 1850s.ï¿½ It has post and beam pegged construction.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Gehlen Barn
description: This magnificent three-story limestone barn, one of the oldest (arguably built in 1839) in Iowa, sits in the middle of this historic Luxembourger village.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Zelle Barn
description: This is a 19th century family farms with one of the few barns left in Scott County.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Ulch Barn
description: This barn, built around 1905, is unique in that it is very primitive.ï¿½ The barn is used in farming.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Stromeyer Barn
description: The Stromeyer farm is a beloved historic family farm. The barn was restored by the family.ï¿½ A pioneer cemetery can be seen from the barn.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Michels Barn
description: Pegged barn was built in 1926 and has been in the same family for three generations.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Peters Barn
description: Henry and Florence Spintig purchased farm about 1903.ï¿½ The main buildings on the home site were present at that time. The barn has been used for farming by the same family since 1934.The barn is interesting because it has cut out squares incorporated into the beams.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Mulford Barn
description: Farm was originally owned byï¿½ Henry Felkner, prosperous miller and farmer, who boughtï¿½ the land in 1837.The 30x67-foot barn is considered a Civil War barn and was built between 1840 and 1870.ï¿½ Old battens are attached with square nails.ï¿½ The framing employs hewn timber posts and beams. The barn was built in a single building ï¿½campaignï¿½ making it a large barn for not having an expansion.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Schneckloth Crib
description: Herbert Schneckloth, prominent Iowa farmer, whose family emigrated from Germany in 1854, built the landmark round crib in 1926.ï¿½ Work on the 50-feet in diameter structure was done with hand tools.ï¿½ The foundation was dug and poured by hand using a shovel and one-third of a bag of home mix at a time.ï¿½ Handmade forms were used to pour the concrete.ï¿½ The ventilation block tile and matching solid tile were brought from Adel by train and horse-drawn wagons.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Cutkomp Barn
description: Barn was originally built by Lewis Cutkomp in 1911.ï¿½ Native lumber was harvested on the place for the barn which was put together with wooden pegs.ï¿½ Cutkomp bought the farm in the late 1800s, and it has remained in the family.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: McBroom-Hargis Barn
description: Article in Madison County paper (1884) discussed this barn, ï¿½It would be the largest barn in this part of the county.ï¿½ï¿½ It has a wooden track, post and beam, pegs and was designed by I.F. Carter of De Soto.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Murphy Barn
description: Primitive historic barn has horse stalls, milking area, hog house, corn crib, cattle feeding area, and hay loft.ï¿½ Barn is still used for agriculture.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Vandewater Barn
description: Barn was built by Henry Vandewater in 1911 and has been in the family since.ï¿½ It has notched beams, pegs, mortise and tendon joints and a memorable wooden cupola.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Kosman Barn
description: Barn, built in 1907, was the scene of large barn dances.ï¿½ Barn has always been used for horses and cows.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Parsons Barn
description: This is a small, but important, Pennsylvania style barn built for practical purposes rather than tradition on a gorgeous site above a village. The National Register barn was built in 1869.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Jones Barn
description: One of the largest barns in the area was built in 1917 and is unusual.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Hansen Barn
description: Corn crib holds 7000 bushels of ear corn, and in the center of crib is storage for 4000 bushels of small grain.ï¿½ In middle of crib is a bucket system that transports ear corn to the top of the corncrib and releases it into multiple outlets.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Horace Hendrickson Barn
description: Barn was built in 1894.ï¿½ Farm was purchased by owner's great-grandfather after arriving from Norway. This was one of five farms he bought - one for each son.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Harvey Barn
description: Farm was homesteaded in 1899.ï¿½ Dan Harvey's great grandparents built the barn in 1927.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Conover Barn
description: Barn was built around 1900 and used by C.B. Conover and his son, C.B., Jr., for their outstanding Belgian draft horses.ï¿½ Harry Linn, Iowa's secretary of agriculture, gave draft horse demonstrations here.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Ellingson Barn
description: Barn can be seen from Dr. Borlaug's farm, half a mile away.ï¿½ The family farm has been beautifully restored.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Palmer Barn
description: Rock is from nearby quarry using teams and wagons.ï¿½ Framing of barn was oak harvested from own woodlands.ï¿½ Portable sawmill was brought to saw logs.ï¿½ Some 200-300 men came for a one day barn raising; each man given a new hammer.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Kruger Barn
description: Large dairy barn was built in 1915 and has been in family for 50 years.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Hinsenbrock Barn
description: Pegged barn (36x70) was built into a hill in 1878 by Peder Bakke, an original Norwegian settler in the county.ï¿½ Barn retains original wooden hay drop for loose hay and has unusual double support rafters.ï¿½ There are hand-hewn timbers, and pegs are in the same condition as when they were made.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Blazek Barn
description: Distinguished large barn had a drive-through center where teams of horses pulled and unloaded full loads of hay.ï¿½ Barn dances were held in mow in early 1900s.

title: Wooster Barn
description: Mr. Wooster's grandfather built this barn in 1896.ï¿½ It has always been used in the family farming operation and still is.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Buckley Barn
description: Barn was built in 1915 on land given to family by President Buchanan.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Redman Barn
description: Barn was built in 1916 and has been owned by two different families.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Anstey Barn
description: In 1878, George Anstey, who emigrated from England, bought 880 acres in Cass County and began raising purebred Herefords.ï¿½ By 1927 every major Hereford show winner is the US was a product of an Anstey-bred dam.ï¿½ The barn is still used for the family cattle business.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Ed Sextro Crib
description: Landmark corn crib was built early 1900s. One of the oldest cribs in the area.ï¿½ The late Mr. Sextro cared so much about this crib that it was the cover of his funeral program.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Hamann Barn
description: This distinguished landmark barn was built in 1907 and served for years as the Worthwhile Frost Dairy Farm.ï¿½ It has dowel or wooden pin type construction on the upper beams and cross members.ï¿½ It has post and beam construction.ï¿½ The silo was constructed after the top window and roofed structure were completed.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Buck Barn
description: Barn is an example of how a potential tear-down can be turned into a jewel.ï¿½ It has a wonderful cupola.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Thurmond-Adams Barn
description: Owner recently inherited old tongue and groove barn (36 x 63 feet), with two-inch vertical siding, and two acres from his uncle.ï¿½ He has made the once sad-looking structure a Williams landmark.ï¿½ (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Dobbin Round Barn
description: 1917 barn was a pre-cut structure designed and made to order by Gordon Van Tine, Davenport, for $6000.ï¿½ Carpenters like Ike Ingersol and Amos Thompson assembled the numbered pieces into the 65-foot diameter barn with silo in the middle.ï¿½ï¿½(Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Boriskey Barn
description: Barn known as "long horse barn on 30" was manufactured by Super Structures, Albert Lea, Minnesota, and built in 1958.ï¿½ Native lumber in horse stalls.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Kaufman Barn
description: Early Iowa Settlers 30x80-foot bank barn is an early Iowa barn which was recently restored.ï¿½ The farm was homesteaded in the 1850s.ï¿½ Barn has table roof, large rolling doors on a track, entirely constructed from wood.ï¿½ A dirt floor remains with its original milk stanchions, horse stalls, long beam construction.ï¿½ The haymow door slides down the front of the barn on a track suspended by two large counter weights.ï¿½ Two log structures and a stone house are on the property.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Beeler Barn
description: Barn is in what was a strong German settlement.ï¿½ Barn was built by the Burger brothers including one who became the first county agent in Iowa.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Cecil Gillespie Barn
description: Unique barn was built in 1874 by W.W. George.ï¿½ The property has been in the same family since 1870.ï¿½ It is located on Old Bluff Road which carried early settlers to Council Bluffs, and is a special small barn.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Oswald Barn
description: Beef barn was designed in the 1930s and can be converted into a show pavilion to seat 1000.ï¿½ Pure-bred Angus were developed there by Dr. C.R. Harken, Osceola physician.ï¿½ J.C. Penney often visited the farm.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Bartelt Barn
description: The owners saw this landmark barn falling into disrepair and subsequently bought and restored it.ï¿½ It is peg and post basement barn with a limestone foundation.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Partridge Barn
description: Barn (56x32) built in 1930 by William Massey who wanted the largest and fanciest barn in the area.ï¿½ It was built prior to the Depression, and he lost the farm.ï¿½ Blocks delivered by train from Lineville.ï¿½ From there it was 10 miles by horse and wagon.ï¿½ Barn is in beautiful area.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Mehlisch Barn
description: Wendish carpenter, Chris Muschick, built the barn in 1905.ï¿½ Barn was painted white in 1916 according to date on inside wall.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Kenan Barn
description: This brick barn, built in the late 1800s, has a matching corn crib.ï¿½ Barn has the original rope pulley and forks.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Schroeder Barn
description: Barn (48x50) was built in 1900 and has roof rafter haymow with haymow door and track in tact.ï¿½ The foundation is river rock.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Trenkamp Barn
description: Barn was built by Justin Berg in 1926.ï¿½ Bernard and Correna Trenkamp purchased the farm in 1945 and used it for dairy and horses.ï¿½ When they retired in 1974, Steve and Doris purchased the farm.ï¿½ Steve has been restoring the barn using native lumber when possible.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Martens Barn
description: Barns were built in the 1870s possibly by A.M. Peters who settled the property in 1868.ï¿½ Fred Martens' grandfather purchased the farm in 1915.ï¿½ Ron McBroom, a tour coordinator, generously donated time and hard work toward the restoration of this barn, after learning that it was vulnerable, because he thought it should be preserved.ï¿½ The north barn was the cattle barn and crib; the south barn was used for horses.ï¿½ A manure bucket system runs on an S-curve track around the basement of this barn.ï¿½ At some time, an old homesteader's claim shack was moved between the two barns for additional storage.ï¿½ Martensdale is named for the family.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Miller Barn
description: Gabled barn was built in teens or twenties.ï¿½ Has center hay storage from ground to roof.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Riessen Barn
description: Barn is 40x 80 and has space for 10 teams of horses on the east side of barn and 26 milk cows on the west side.ï¿½ Silo and silo shed were built in 1917.ï¿½ West addition was put on in 1961.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: McCaughey Barn
description: Howard Lesan built this large (40- x 80-foot) barn for his dairy, the first in the county.ï¿½ This barn was built in 1929 after a fire took an earlier one.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Wilson Barn
description: Pegged horse barn was built around 1883.ï¿½ Barn is full-floored with limestone foundation.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Draman Barn
description: This small stone barn, probably built in the mid-to late 1870, is a jewel in the center of Iowa.ï¿½ The barn has a gabled roof and was a cow barn.ï¿½ It is on the National Historic Register, listed as "Duff Barn."  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Smith Barn
description: Pegged barn was built around 1920.ï¿½ Bark still remains on some of the interior lumber.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Blake Barn
description: This 33x39-foot barn actually sits on Benson Street, which crosses over I-35.ï¿½ Interestingly, the barn is highly visible from I-35.ï¿½ The barn was built in 1902, has a gambrel roof, and a stairway to the loft.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: West Barn
description: In a nostalgic hidden corner of Clarke County is this 30x 60-foot pegged barn.ï¿½ Barn is unusual in that it has a large hay mow door on each end of the barn.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Shetland Pony Farm Barn
description: The barn, built after the turn of the century, was created with redwood from the Northwest.ï¿½ During the 1950s, the barn, built in the 1930s, became the center of activity for a renowned Shetland pony operation.ï¿½ Ponies were sold to various catalogs including Spiegel and possibly Sears.ï¿½ The owner was a Leon native from Chicago who had the nickname Cowpuncher.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Ross Farm Barn
description: This farm is referred to as on "the old Bedford Ross place."ï¿½ Bedford Ross bred, raised and exhibited American Saddlebreds, Percherons, and a Belgian, all of which he had stallions he stood at stud.ï¿½ He also had a Hackney-Shetland pony stud.ï¿½ He kept horses and worked them on the farm until seven or eight years before he died in 1998.ï¿½ The barn was built in the 1930s.ï¿½ Farm is owned by Gabe Adair, who is from an "old" area family.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Round Barn
description: The 82' x 68' round barn, with a Gothic curved roof, was designed by Peter Tonsfeldt in 1918.ï¿½ He wanted a structure to show off his Polled Hereford bull and purebred cattle.  During the Depression years, the Tonsfeldt family sold their west LeMars farm to Herman Lang.ï¿½ Following Lang's death in 1980, the farm was offered at auction, where the Langley brothers purchased the property.  They donated the historic round barn to the Plymouth County Fairgrounds, and the barn was moved to its present location.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Old Iowa State Farm Barn (Hullinger Farm)
description: This barn, built about 1940, is on a historic farm.ï¿½ The farm was part of the Southern Iowa Pasture Farmsï¿½orchestrated by the Iowa Agricultural Experiment Station and the Iowa Agricultural Extension Service in the winter of 1935 to establish a pasture improvement demonstration project through the U.S. Forest Service.ï¿½ This was during the Depression, and that same year the Land Policy Section of the Agricultural Adjustment Administration was transferred to the Land Utilization Division of the Resettlement Administration where emphasis was on developing jobs for men who were certified on relief.ï¿½ After World War II, the farm became a USDA research site.ï¿½ Much of the research at the farm at that time was directed by Dr. L.N. Hazel, distinguished Iowa State University animal science professor.ï¿½ In 1955, the farm's title was transferred to the Iowa State University Agriculture Experiment Station.ï¿½ The farm was sold by the Board of Regents in 1969.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Hoffman Barn
description: Hoffman barnï¿½was built at the turn of the century by Theodor Hoffman.ï¿½ The land, on which the barn sits, was homesteaded by Dennis Hoffman in 1870.ï¿½ Most of the wood used in building the barn came from cottonwood trees on the farm.ï¿½ The lower level was used for work horses.ï¿½ The stalls and bunks remain.ï¿½ The barn was the scene of many barn dances.ï¿½ Lawerence Welk played at some of those dances.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: John Lucken Barn
description: This barn was originally owned by Harvey and and Bob Lias.ï¿½ Bob, 82, recalls his grandfather building the barn when he was 12.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Vande Kieft Barn
description: This barn was built in 1940.ï¿½ It was converted from a cow barn to a stable for the family's draft and quarter horses.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Evan Kraayenbrink Barn
description: This barn was built in the 1880s and is still used to provide shelter for dairy calves.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Oostra Corn Crib Granary
description: This crib has grain bins over the alley and an inside elevator.ï¿½ It was built in 1956 and has storage for 4000 bushels of ear corn and 3000 bushels of grain.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Gary and Alura Otto Barn
description: This barn was built in the 1920's and housed cows, horses and sows on one side of the barn.ï¿½ Hay was stacked in the center from the ground up, with grain bins above.ï¿½ The other side of the barn was a loafing area for cattle.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Smith Family Trust Barn
description: This barn is owned by grandchildren of original owner, William Smith, whose family purchased the farm with the barn in 1907.ï¿½ (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Cherokee County Park Barn
description: This barnï¿½is a 52' x 120' foot barn built in the early 1900's.ï¿½ Originally owned by Wayne Little and used as a loafing barn for dairy cattle; now is a main feature at the Silver Sioux Recreation Area on the Little Sioux River.ï¿½ Preservation, Restoration has become an economic question for Cherokee County.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Alvin Melton Granary
description: This granary was built in 1910.ï¿½ It is believed to be the first granary in Cherokee County.ï¿½ This impressive building still has the dump cups, chain and switching mechanism, used to fill the four large overhead bins, and the attached "engine room" where horses, and later tractors, supplied the power.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Otto Family Barn
description: This barn, built in 1904, is part of Pioneer Henry J. Otto's 1884 homestead.ï¿½ This early leader in the Hanover community had 16 children.ï¿½ It is the 24 remaining cousins, of the original 64, who want to preserve their grandfather's barn.ï¿½ The barn was used for work horses, cattle and hay storage.ï¿½ It is the current home of Aaron Hinkeldey.ï¿½ Virdene Otto is the leader for the barn preservation.  (Source: Iowa Barn Foundation)

title: Memorial Union
description: This is a multi-functional dance hall, hosting everything from dances to wedding receptions, fish frys, auctions, and other community activities.  It was built in 1949-50 by the local American Legion Post.  There is an oak dance floor.  (Source: Iowa Ballroom Project)

title: Surf Ballroom
description: To many, the Surf Ballroom is an American cultural icon as well as an important historical landmark. The original Surf Ballroom (pictured above) was built in 1933 and destroyed by fire in 1947. The Surf Ballroom was rebuilt in 1948, across the street from the original location.  The Surf Ballroom has a capacity of 2,100 and accomodates visitors with 30,000 square feet of entertainment area, including a 6,300 square foot dance floor. It is often filled to capacity with the music of internationally known performers.  The Surf got its name (and motif) from the desire of the original owners to create a ballroom that resembled an ocean beach club. The murals on the back walls were hand-painted to depict pounding surf, swaying palm trees, sailboats and lighthouses. The furnishings were bamboo and rattan and the ambience that of a south sea island. The stage is surrounded by palm trees and the clouds overhead make it seem as if you were dancing outside under the stars.  On January 27, 2009, the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame and Museum (Cleveland, Ohio) dedicated the Surf Ballroom as a historic rock and roll landmark as part of the Museum's ongoing Landmark Series, which identifies locations in America that are significant to the origins and development of rock and roll.  The plaque reads: "There are few buildings in existence today that represent a complete shift in our musical history. As the last concert venue for Buddy Holly, Ritchie Valens and J.P. "The Big Bopper" Richardson, the Surf is the bedrock of where the sound and attitude of rock and roll changed forever."  (Source: Iowa Ballroom Project)

title: Val Air Ballroom
description: In 1939 the Val Air was opened by Mr. Tom Archer on property purchased from the old Wilson Tire Company.ï¿½ it first opened as an open air dance pavilion, thus the name Val Air, and was later changed to the enlosed stucture in 1954, that you see today. It was a part of a chain Archer owned with ballrooms in such locations as Des Moines, Cedar Rapids, Marion, Creston, Sioux City all in Iowa, Dell Rapids & Sioux Falls in South Dakota, Omaha, Nb and St. Joseph, Mo. The Val Air was the "King" of Des Moines ballrooms in the 30's and 40's, drawing the likes of Glen Miller, Louis Armstrong, and the ever popular Lawrence Welk. With the dawning of the rock era, all the top names played archer's Val Air. From Roy Orbison to The Everly Brothers, from the Ventures to The Trashmen and the Fabulous Flippers.  They all called the Val Air their "home base" in Des Moines when traveling the Midwest ballroom circuit.  (Source: Iowa Ballroom Project)

title: Duncan Community Ballroom
description: Located in the small Czech village of Duncan, Iowa is a beautiful dance hall known as the Duncan Community Ballroom. This ballroom proves that the small towns in America's heartland are still active today with great pride in volunteerism as well as their heritage.ï¿½In September of 1899, 13 men gathered at a country school and organized the Catholic Workman, Branch 51. As the town grew, a community hall was needed. In 1922, members of Branch 51 organized the construction of a new brick community hall. On the night of the grand opening the Duncan Band played, while a generator and Model-T engine hooked together supplied lights in the hall. The Community Hall was a very active place and held many fundraisers, dances, and Czech plays. June 25, 1951 was a disastrous day for Duncan, Iowa. A tornado arose from the southwest and destroyed the Community Hall, St. Wenceslaus Catholic Church, homes, businesses, and farm places. Through the strength and faith of the community, the town of Duncan was rebuilt. Through collaborative efforts, a new Duncan Ballroom was built. The community that worked together could once again celebrate together. Many of the popular old time bands played in Duncan ï¿½ the Six Fat Dutchmen, Babe Wagner, Elmer Scheid, and Roman Rezac to name a few. Local bands also played for dances, including Malek Bros. Accordian Band and the Hrubes Huskers. In the late 1970's more room was needed. An addition was constructed, including a new bar, restrooms, and extra seating.  (Source: Iowa Ballroom Project)

title: Col Ballroom
description: The Col is one of lowa's oldest operating ballrooms having been built in November of 1914 by the late Leo Kerker as a replacement for an earlier wooden ballroom that was destroyed by fire.  The original ballroom was known as The Coliseum. In 1991, the ballroom underwent a major renovation that included extensive brick cleaning. The ornate balcony also underwent extensive renovation as well as new carpeting and drapes. The owner of The Col during most of it's historic years was Don Wachel of Davenport.  Don has been one of the most highly regarded professionals in the ballroom industry nationally including being past president of the National Ballrooms Operators Association (NBOA).  (Source: Iowa Ballroom Project)

title: Lakeside Ballroom
description: Lakeside was built in 1927 in Guttenberg, Iowa and was a popular establishment during the prohibition era. The structure, built by William H. Kann and Sons, was erected at a cost of $27,000 and had a dance floor 50 x 160 feet. The dance floor was built with 1 ï¿½ï¿½ hardwood maple on springs so that people would not get tired when dancing. They painted LAKESIDE in large letter on the roof of the building to use for aerial dead-recognizing navigation, the only method of navigation at the time. Lindberg and other pioneer aviators used Lakeside as a checkpoint flying from Minneapolis to Chicago and St. Louis. Lakeside was nearly lost in the flood of 1965 when there was 5 feet of water covering the dance floor. The US Army Corps of Engineers loaded it with dynamite for demolition in case it floated into the Lock and Dam.  (Source: www.lakesideballroomonline.com)

title: Laramar Ballroom
description: Fort Dodge had a National Guard infantry company (Company G, Fifty-Sixth Infantry), but its armory building was thought to be too small and too far downtown. The Quist Band's finances would be stabilized by becoming a regimental band; and since there would be additional rent coming from the state if Fort Dodge had a regimental band, a new armory building was proposed. The Fort Dodge Commercial Club guaranteed the raising of $8,000 for that purpose, and in 1904 the new National Guard Armory was built near the corner of 1st Avenue North and 7th Street. It served as the band's rehearsal hall until the end of 1910 when the band severed their relationship with the National Guard. The armory building survives today as the Laramar Ballroom.

title: Avalon Ballroom
description: Avalon Ballroom was built in 1937.  At the time it was built it's size (60'x110') made it one of the largest structures of it's kind in western Iowa.  The Remsen Jaycees and the Remsen Community Action Club have undertaken significant remodeling of the ballroom.  It was inducted in to the Iowa Rock & Roll Music Association's Hall of Fame in 1999.  (Source: Iowa Ballroom Project)

title: Inwood Ballroom
description: Beginning in 1920, local and regional bands began playing at the newly constructed pavilion in Spillvilleï¿½s Riverside Park. From the 1930s through the 1950s, renovations and expansion efforts were undertaken and national acts started playing at the Inwood. Lawrence Welk, Louis Armstrong, Earl Hines, the Six Fat Dutchmen, Leo Greco, Guy Lombardo and others all performed to sell out crowds. The first ï¿½Teen Danceï¿½ was held on May 27, 1960. Teen hops flourished, masterminded by Darrell Winkie and his famous ï¿½Wink-I Pepsi Parties.ï¿½ Winkie and his portable deejay service supplied the music for those early rock and roll shows. Live rock shows began in 1965 with the performance by the legendary Byrds who had the number one hit that summer, ï¿½Mr. Tambourine Man.ï¿½ For the next 10 years a whoï¿½s who of rock and roll bands came from throughout the country to perform at the Inwood. National acts appearing included Bobby Goldsboro, The Stillroven, Dee Jay & the Runaways, the Pete Klint Quintet, The Buckinghams, the Fabulous Flippers, The I.BT.C., Enoch Somkey and ShowTime Parts 1 & 2. Although many ballrooms have fallen by the wayside, the Inwood Ballroom is still operating today as the quintessential site for wedding dances, polka parties and special musical events.  (Source: Iowa Ballroom Project)

title: Walcott Coliseum
description: The Eastern Iowa Polk Club sponsors monthly dances at the Walcott Coliseum. The reception hall can accommodate up to 700 guests.

title: Dance Mor Ballroom
description: The Dance Mor Ballroom has been in continuous operation since 1932.  The all-wood structure with crawlspace and suspended maple dance floor is an example of true craftsmanship.  It was inducted in to the Iowa Rock & Roll Music Association's Hall of Fame in 2005.  (Source: Iowa Ballroom Project)

title: Ponderosa Ballroom
description: The former Walford School has become the Ponderosa Ballroom.  It has a 4,000 square foot wood floor and can seat up to 550.

title: Electric Park Ballroom
description: The "new" Electric Park Ballroom was constructed in 1934, after the original ballroom was lost in a fire.  The ballroom is operated by the National Cattle Congress.   It has been inducted in to the Iowa Rock & Roll Music Association's Hall of Fame.  (Source: Iowa Ballroom Project)

title: Nob Hill Ballroom
description: Nob Hill Ballroom was built in 1937 as a dance hall catering to square dancers.  It was  inducted in to the Iowa Rock & Roll Music Association's Hall of Fame in 2012.

title: McElroy Auditorium
description: McElroy Auditorium was built in 1919 and renovated in 1936.  The auditorium's construction materials, roof design and room design make it acoustically well-suited for concerts. It has been in continous operation since 1919, making it one of the oldest arenas in the nation.

title: Lake Robbins Ballroom
description: The Robbins family began building this ballroom in 1929, and completed it in 1931.  On opening night, rain poured down and the mud was knee deep - but cars lined both sides of the road and the palce was packed!  Lake Robbins Ballroom was inducted in to the Iowa Rock & Roll Music Association's Hall of Fame in 2007.  (Source: Iowa Ballroom Project)

title: Sioux City Art Center
description: The Sioux City Art Center presents exhibitions of local, national and international artists.  The Education Department is dedicated to providing people of all ages with educational opportunities that encourage creative expression, develop artistic skills, and foster appreciation for the visual arts through a variety of classes, tours, and programs.

title: Blank Park Zoo
description: Theï¿½missionï¿½of the Blank Park Zoo is to inspire an appreciation of the natural world throughï¿½conservation, education and recreation.

title: Blanden Memorial Art Museum
description: The Blanden Art Museum is located in the Historic Oak Hill District of Fort Dodge, a city on the Des Moines River settled in the 1850s and developed as a mining, agricultural and commercial center of Webster County. The museum is a neo-classical public building constructed on private land and financed by Charles Granger Blanden. The museum and grounds were donated to the City of Fort Dodge at completion in 1932.

title: Charles H. MacNider Art Museum
description: The Charles H. MacNider Museum is a non-profit, municipally owned institution conceived in 1964 and opened by 1966 in Mason City, Iowa. The museum exhibits and interprets a permanent collection of American art; temporary exhibitions of art; provides art classes for all ages; offers enriching arts programs; and maintains an art library.

title: Cedar Falls Community Theatre
description: This is a hip, fun and happening place to be for live performance in the Midwest. Great plays are performed live on stage throughout the year. Some are musicals and many are great comedies and farces that have proven to be hits. This traditional theatre, with a main floor and balcony, was built in 1910 and restored in 1994.

title: Des Moines Metro Opera Inc
description: The Des Moines Metro Opera is a nationally recognized progressive opera company that has taken its place amont America's leading opera festivals.  The company produces a Summer Opera Festival that offers diverse operatic works at the highest artistic standards, provides quality opportunities for American-trained talent in all facets of opera performance, develops audiences of all ages through year-round educational programs, and serves the region as a cultural leader.

title: Des Moines Art Center
description: The not-for-profit Des Moines Art Center engages diverse local and international audiencesï¿½with the art ofï¿½today throughï¿½its museum and school, adding to the cultural record through collections and programs. FREE admission supported by Principal Financial Group Foundation, Inc. and Art Center members.

title: Des Moines Playhouse
description: The Des Moines Community Playhouse was founded in 1919 by members of the Iowa Press and Authors Club. Although the Little Theatre Movement was causing similar enterprises to spring up across the country, the Playhouse is unique in that it has operated continuously, under various names and in various homes, since its founding. With more than 90 years of uninterrupted service, the Playhouse is among the six oldest continuously-operating community theatres in the U.S. It is also the second largest community theatre in the U.S.

title: Figge Art Museum
description: The Figge Art Museum actively serves the public by promoting appreciation and creation of visual art through education, and by collecting, conserving and exhibiting art. As a vital, responsive institution, the Museum brings art and people together, expands the knowledge and love of art, and enriches the life of the community through the power of art."

title: Des Moines Performing Arts
description: Des Moines Performing Arts is central Iowaï¿½s premier not-for-profit performing organization. They present professional touring production direct from Broadway, and since our opening have positioned Des Moines as a top destination for world-class productions on their first national tours.

title: Dubuque Museum of Art
description: Established in 1874, the Dubuque Museum of Art is one of Iowa's oldest cultural institutions.  The Dubuque Museum of Art seeks to excite, engage and educate constituents through the presentation of collections, exhibitions and programming.

title: Des Moines Symphony Association
description: The mission of the Des Moines Symphony Association is to enrich, educate and entertain our community by performing great orchestral music. Led by Music Directorï¿½Joseph Giuntaï¿½for the past 25 years, the Orchestra has established an outstanding national reputation as one of the countryï¿½s leading regional orchestras, performing a regular series of Masterworks, Pops, Family, and Education Concerts, as well as performing for special events. With the establishment in 2003 of the Des Moines Symphony Academy, the organization is one of only a handful of American orchestras to sponsor an Academy of Music as an integral part of its core mission and the Symphony & Academy together are now the largest employer of professional artists in Iowa.

title: Dubuque Symphony Orchestra
description: The mission of the Dubuque Symphony Orchestra is to engage the tri-state community and enrich its quality of life through live musical performances and educational programs.

title: Englert Civic Theatre
description: The mission of The Englert Theatre is to own, maintain and operate The Englert Theatre as a community arts center and performance space, enhancing the vitality of Iowa City's historic downtown by preserving its last historic theater. The Englert Theatre provides diverse programming, educational opportunities and exposure to the performing and visual arts. Their focus is on highlighting the talents of local performers, artists and ensembles as well as hosting regional, national and international touring performances.

title: Grand Opera House
description: The Grand Opera House Foundation, a non-profit corporation owns this magnificent facility. A board of directors provides guidance to our paid staff and a large roster of dedicated volunteers. Funding is provided principally by ticket sales, plus an annual campaign, show sponsorships, playbill ad sales and rentals.  As 21st century audiences enjoy this beautiful theater it is a living tribute to the heritage and traditions of past generations of actors, musicians, choreographers, costumers, stage hands, set designers, managers and the visionary leaders of 1890 who created Dubuque's Grand Opera House.

title: Iowa Arboretum
description: The purpose of the Iowa Arboretum is to be an inspiring educational and recreational resource demonstrating the value and use of trees, shrubs and herbaceous plants in the landscape to all Iowans. This unique showplace has continued to expand and contains over 4,000 accessioned woody and herbaceous plants. It is one of the largest and most diverse displays of plants that can be successfully grown in Iowa. In addition, the Arboretum manages a 330-acre native woodland featuring century old oaks and native grasses.

title: Iowa Youth Chorus
description: The Iowa Youth Chorus is a nonprofit organization that develops fresh voices, fosters a life-long love of music, encourages children to follow their passions and motivates them to set high goals and work hard to achieve them. The result is a group of exceptional young people who come together to delight audiences with a musical repertoire drawing from various time periods and worldwide destinations.
